<HEADLINE> Nyerere's Health Improves Slightly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, October 2 (Xinhua) -- The health of Tanzania's
former president Julius Nyerere admitted to a London hospital for
leukemia has improved slightly but he is still in a critical
condition, an official statement said on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Doctors at the Saint Thomas Hospital said the 77-year-old
African statesman has hopes for recovery but still needs a life
support machine in the next two to three days, said the statement
issued by the President's Press Secretary Geoffrey Nkurlu.
</P>
<P>
Nyerere, suffering from chronic lymphocytic leukemia, was
admitted to the hospital eight days ago. He is under
round-the-clock intensive care with his families at his bedside.
</P>
<P>
Tanzanian President Benjamin Mkapa has asked Tanzanian people
to pray for Nyerere, while the first lady Anna Mkapa is offering
help in London, Nkurlu said.
</P>
<P>
Medical checks have found that Nyerere's blood pressure is
normal, jaundice complications are decreasing, and his lungs are
less affected.
</P>
<P>
In Tanzanian capital Dar es Salaam, people kept on listening to
the radio or watching TV to learn the development of Nyerere's
conditions.
</P>
<P>
The illness of Nyerere has also caused concerns in other
African countries. Students at the University of Zimbabwe are
conducting prayers for the major figure in post-colonial Africa,
said the press secretary to Tanzanian Prime Minister Frederick
Sumaye, who is visiting the southern African country.
</P>
<P>
Nyerere led the then Tanganyika to gain independence from
Britain in 1961 and masterminded its union with Zanzibar isles in
1964 to form Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
After retiring as president in 1985, he played an advisory role
in both Tanzanian politics and African affairs. He tirelessly
mediated Burundi peace talks since 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
