<HEADLINE> Somalis Dying of Famine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, October 2 (Xinhua) -- Somalia's central and
southern regions are facing famine as a result of drought and
local authorities have characterized the situation as "desperate".
</P>
<P>
The international aid agencies have reportedly not yet
responded to the worsening humanitarian crises in these regions
despite their announcement to resume relief operations last week.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations suspended aid operations in the country
after the killing of the UNICEF doctor, Ayub Sheikh Yarow, last
month.
</P>
<P>
The most serious regions are the Gedo, Bay and Bakol where
death toll exceeds 23 people mainly children and elderly everyday.
 Reports from Bakol region indicate that 12 people die every day
for famine and starvation after over 20 villages surrounding the
main town of Huddor had fallen short of water.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of people and their herds are now on the move
towards the main towns of Huddor, Tieglow and Baidoa in search of
water and food. " But the concern is that the children, elderly
people and the cattle can't make the long journeys on foot," said
Hussein Abdi Mohamed, a local doctor operating in the region.
</P>
<P>
Similar crises are also being reported in the central regions
of Galgudud and Mudug. Yussuf Hassan Eyow, the governor of
Galgudud region, said most of the water wells in the region had
dried up while others can not operate for lack of spare parts.
</P>
<P>
Eyow said there's serious food and water shortages in the
regions and warned against humanitarian catastrophe unless
something is done quickly. 
</P>
</TEXT>
