<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt to Ask for Review of Uruguay Round: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, October 2 (Xinhua) -- Egypt will ask for a review of the
Uruguay Round trade pact because its implementation is not in the
interest of developing countries, Egyptian Minister of Trade and
Supply Ahmed Gowaili said here Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Developing countries have a general understanding that the
Uruguay Round's application was "highly arbitrary," Gowaili said
while addressing the inaugural session of the general conference
of the G-15 chambers of commerce and industry.
</P>
<P>
The Uruguay Round, a trade pact named after the country where
the negotiations of the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade,
predecessor of the World Trade Organization (WTO), began in 1986,
lays down procedures for opening up markets.
</P>
<P>
The developing states have blamed the Uruguay Round for working
for "the good of developed countries and against that of the
developing world," Gowaili said.
</P>
<P>
Egypt would push for a review of the pact at next month's WTO
meeting in Seattle, the United States, he added.
</P>
<P>
The conference of the G-15 chambers of commerce and industry is
to focus on the impact of world policies on the development of the
developing countries and to deal with the challenges of the new
world order, Egypt's Middle East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Gowaili said Egypt will host a G-15 summit in 2000. The country
organized a summit in May 1998.
</P>
<P>
The G-15, formed in 1989, comprises Algeria, Argentina, Brazil,
Chile, Egypt, India, Indonesia, Jamaica, Kenya, Malaysia, Mexico,
Nigeria, Peru, Senegal, Sri Lanka, Venezuela and Zimbabwe. 
</P>
</TEXT>
