<HEADLINE> U.N. Reports "Disastrous" Conditions in Parts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, October 2 (Xinhua) -- The head of the United
Nations humanitarian operations has said that thousands of people
were starving to death in an area of the Republic of Congo, U.N.
officials said here Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Sergio Vieira de Mello, the U.N. under-secretary-general for
humanitarian affairs, reported "disastrous" conditions in Kinkala,
some 80 kilometers from the nation's capital of Brazzaville, with
thousands close to death because of severe food shortages.
</P>
<P>
In recent weeks, 10 people a day have died from starvation,
he said.
</P>
<P>
The first U.N. humanitarian mission since fighting broke out
last December in the African country travelled with a military
escort to Kinkala Wednesday. The team included relief workers from
U.N. agencies, donor and government representatives, the officials
said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, de Mello appealed to the donor community to provide
urgent and generous funding to U.N. agencies and non-governmental
organizations in the Republic of Congo to enable them to provide
much-needed food and medicines.
</P>
<P>
The Republic of Congo was caught up in the turmoil from the
large neighboring Democratic Republic of Congo several years ago.
The conflict resulted in more than 10,000 deaths in Brazzaville
alone. 
</P>
</TEXT>
