<HEADLINE> SAfrica VP Urges to Reduce Dependence on Gold </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 2 (Xinhua) -- South African Vice
President Jacob Zuma urged on Saturday to reduse his country's
dependence on the sale of gold.
</P>
<P>
The vice president said at the opening of the annual summit of
the National Economic Development and Labor Council (Nedlac) at
Gallagher Estate in Midrand near Johannesburg that despite the
"meteoric" rise of the gold price there was a need to find ways to
reduce South Africa's continued dependence on the sale of gold.
</P>
<P>
"This makes us extremely vulnerable to such price fluctuations
and the whims of nations that, while consuming large amounts of
gold, do not have any role in its production," Zuma said.
</P>
<P>
It was encouraging that the percentage of exports accounted for
by gold had declined by 55 percent to under 20 percent over the
last 20 years, Zuma said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
