<HEADLINE> U.N. Launches Plan to Better Health System in Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, October 2 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations has
presented goals and guidelines aimed at rebuilding an efficient
and modern health service for Kosovo, the Yugoslav province, by
using international humanitarian aid, U.N. officials said here
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The six-month plan, launched Friday in Kosovo, was developed by
the United Nations Interim Administration Mission in Kosovo
(UNMIK), which is in charge of the civil administration in the
Serbian province, and the World Health Organization (WHO).
</P>
<P>
The plan strives to guide immediate relief efforts, while also
focusing on international aid towards long-term development of a
system to be sustained by the future autonomous Kosovo government,
which is expected to be set up in the wake of proposed elections
organized by the U.N. Mission.
</P>
<P>
"UNMIK is firmly committed to leaving behind a better system
than it found when it assumed the responsibility for the interim
administration in Kosovo," said Hannu Vuori, UNMIK head of
health and social services.
</P>
<P>
A key aspect of the strategy, crafted in consultation with
Kosovar officials, is to reorient the current "hospital-driven"
system towards one focused on family medicine and preventive care.
It also lays out targets for improving children's services and
maternity and mental health care.
</P>
<P>
Since August, UNMIK has attempted to maintain a multi-ethnic
staff at the hospital. Responding to incidents during the past
week, the U.N. Mission began providing armed escorts for some
workers.
</P>
<P>
It is of a big challenge to the U.N. Mission to maintain a
multi-ethnic society in Kosovo simply because most of Serbians and
other non-Albanians were pushed by force out of the autonomous
province, the Yugoslav Government has said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
