<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Major Hospitals Paralyzed in Doctors' </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, October 2 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwean junior doctors' strike
has entered its 11th day and paralyzed Zimbabwe's major hospitals
including Harare Central hospital.
</P>
<P>
Senior doctors and consultants are currently manning the
institutions where only patients in serious conditions are
admitted.
</P>
<P>
Nyasha Masuka, spokesman for the walkout doctors, told the
Zimbabwe News Agency Saturday that the doctors were still holding
consultations with the ministries of Public Service, Labor and
Social Welfare and Health and Child Welfare to resolve their
problems.
</P>
<P>
Masuka said the strike would continue until the government meet
their demands.
</P>
<P>
The government on Friday announced an increase in the junior
doctors' on- call allowances from 472 Zimbabwean dollars (12.4
U.S. dollars) to 1,500 Zimbabwean dollars (39.4 U.S. dollars) a
call on week days and 1,750 Zimbabwean dollars (46 U.S. dollars)
on holidays and over weekends.
</P>
<P>
However the doctors have rejected the offer saying they wanted
their basic salaries to be reviewed because the on-calls were
overtime and not guaranteed.
</P>
<P>
A junior doctor in Zimbabwe earns a gross salary of 15,000
Zimbabwean dollars (394 U.S. dollars) per month.
</P>
<P>
The country's ailing health delivery system has suffered
setbacks because of financial constraints and brain drain to
neighboring countries and Britain where salaries are much better
than at home. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
