<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lions to Be Moved from Marloth Park in S. Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 2 (Xinhua) -- The Mpumalanga Parks Board
(MPB) announced Friday that it would move the resident lions of
Marloth Park, where a person was killed and eaten by a pride
earlier this week, to a holding facility in the Kruger National
Park.
</P>
<P>
The MPB said in a statement that the lions would be tested for
bovine tuberculosis and the final decision on where to move them
would be made, based on the outcome of the tests.
</P>
<P>
The plan, however, is likely to face resistance from residents
of this small town on the Kruger National Park's southern border
in the Mpumalanga Province in northeastern South Africa.
</P>
<P>
Marloth Park property owners association Chairman Brian
Welby-Cooke said there is no conclusive evidence that these lions
were responsible for the death of a man on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
He added that it had also not been conclusively proven that
once a lion had eaten a human they would necessarily become
man-eaters.
</P>
<P>
In a recent survey of owners, 95 percent voted against the
removal of lions in the area.
</P>
<P>
The area is unique as it allows wild animals to roam freely
through the town and the majority of residents do not want this
changed.
</P>
<P>
Officers from MPB will meet with Welby-Cooke and a delegation
of property owners on Saturday to discuss their plan.
</P>
<P>
Jan Muller of the MPB said a group of between 22 and 24 lions
entered the area last year from the Kruger National Park and were
trapped in the town by a flooded river.
</P>
<P>
They subsequently settled in the area and some lost their fear
of humans.
</P>
<P>
At least nine of these lions were responsible for an attack on
stock in a neighboring farm. Six were killed by farmers and the
other three were darted and taken back to the game reserve.
</P>
<P>
"This means that about 12 lions have remained in the area. We
believe that some of these could have been responsible for the
attack on Tuesday night," Muller said.
</P>
<P>
"Because we were unable to isolate the attackers and check one
of their stomach contents for human remains, we have decided to
relocate all of the resident lions."
</P>
<P>
The relocation of the resident lions would not, however, mean
the end of lions in the area, as other lions from the Kruger
National Park will still be able to enter and leave the area.
</P>
<P>
Muller said the hunt for the lions would probably start next
week.
</P>
<P>
Komatipoort police station commissioner Captain Vusi Mdakane
said no workers in the town were reported missing and the dead
person, believed to be a solar panel thief, seemed to have come
from outside the area.
</P>
<P>
He said police were going to nearby villages with the torn
remains of a pair of dark blue trousmrs to see if anyone could
identify them. They were also watching for missing persons reports
in the area to identify the victim.
</P>
<P>
Unconfirmed medical reports indi30:e the victim was a man.
</P>
<P>
Marloth Park Game Ranger Johan van der Walt said this was the
fourth attack in the area but the first fatal one. 
</P>
</TEXT>
