<HEADLINE> Sinn Fein Leader Says Good Friday Deal Could be "Finished" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 2 (Xinhua) -- Northern Ireland's Sinn Fein
leader Gerry Adams said on Saturday that the Good Friday peace
deal was finished if pro-British unionists continued to prevent
the nationalist minority from sharing power.
</P>
<P>
In a speech addressed to a youth conference of Sinn Fein, the
IRA's political wing, held in the Ireland Republic capital of
Dublin, Adams accused the Ulster Unionist party of engaging in a
high risk strategy to keep Irish republicans out of a
power-sharing Northern Ireland executive.
</P>
<P>
He said if Ulster Unionist Party leader David Trimble "does not
face up to his responsibilities then the Good Friday agreement is
finished," the Reuters reported.
</P>
<P>
Trimble has refused to set up a power-sharing administration
with Sinn Fein until the Irish Republican Army (IRA) hands in
weapons from its 30-year-long war against British rule.
</P>
<P>
He delivered the warning ahead of a round-table meeting with
Trimble on Monday as part of a review of the peace process chaired
by U.S. Senator George Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
Trimble was expected to speak at a youth conference of his own
party in Belfast later on Saturday.  
</P>
</TEXT>
