<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Resurgence of Gold Bodes Well for South Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 2 (Xinhua) -- The recent rise in the gold
price was good news for South Africa's economy as it save some
jobs in the gold mining industry, Finance Minister Trevor Manuel
said on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
"I believe that there will be some saving of jobs," he told
reporters at Johannesburg International Airport on his return from
the annual joint meetings of the World Bank and the International
Monetary Fund in Washington.
</P>
<P>
"I believe the impact of this will be felt long into the
future. The comeback will allow for longer planning horizons in
the industry," he added.
</P>
<P>
The gold price rocketed by several U.S. dollars an ounce
earlier in the week after an announcement on Sunday by the
European Central Bank that its 15 members would abide by a cap on
gold sales of 400 tons a year.
</P>
<P>
Manuel said the most important element of the European Central
Bank's decision was the message that gold remained significant in
the management of monetary reserves.
</P>
<P>
Lobbying by South Africa among central banks undoubtedly
contributed to the European decision, Manuel said.
</P>
<P>
But Manuel cautioned against over-optimism about the future of
the gold mining industry.
</P>
<P>
"There will always be difficulties, especially given the fact
that a number of mines are as marginal as they are," he said.
</P>
<P>
"The ore bodies are deep and the ore grades are not as high as
they were, making extraction very expensive."
</P>
<P>
On the past week's meetings of the IMF and the World Bank, he
said the focus was clearly on debt relief and poverty alleviation.
</P>
<P>
The spotlight fell largely on Africa, and new countries to
qualify for debt relief included Tanzania. Zambia was also in
line.
</P>
<P>
Efforts to reduce poverty had taken a new direction, and the
World Bank and the IMF would now work together to oversee this
programme, Manuel said.
</P>
<P>
The fresh approach provided for poor countries to submit relief
 strategies with targets which they had drawn up themselves.
</P>
<P>
Manuel said the Southern African Development Community members
would have to work together in some respects, especially with
regard to training and retaining public servants adept in
financial management.
</P>
<P>
"We need to ensure that we have a high quality of service in
our treasuries," Manuel said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
