<HEADLINE> UNMIK "Blue Sky" Begins Broadcasting in Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, October 2 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations "Blue
Sky" public radio Friday went on the air in Kosovo, the Yugoslav
province, with programs of news, music and features around the
clock, U.N. officials said here Saturday.
</P>
<P>
News bulletins, produced entirely by local journalists, are
broadcast daily in Albanian at 7:30 a.m. (local time) and 7:30
p.m. (local time), and in Serbian at 8:30 a.m. (local time) and
8:30 p.m. (local time).
</P>
<P>
The radio also broadcasts news and features on the United
Nations Interim Administration Mission in Kosovo (UNMIK), which
began operation in June in Kosovo under a U.N. resolution, at a
quarter to the hour, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
"Blue Sky" radio is operating with mostly local staff, under
the editorial supervision of the UNMIK. The Swiss Government has
donated studio facilities and technical support staff.
</P>
<P>
The radio station plans to expand news coverage to include
debates, press reviews and phone-in programs, and the programs
will also cover women's issues, youth, culture and humanitarian
topics.
</P>
<P>
Programs in various languages will be added, as will English
lectures.  
</P>
</TEXT>
