<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-02 20:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egyptian Former Militants Ask for Permission to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, October 2 (Xinhua) -- Scores of former Egyptian Islamic
radicals on Saturday asked the government to allow them to set up
a political party which they said will peacefully advocate Islamic
principles.
</P>
<P>
Fifty-five people signed a petition submitted to the
government's Committee of Parties' Affairs, requesting permission
to form The Party of Sharia, or Islamic creed, according to
Mamdouh Ismail, a leader of the group.
</P>
<P>
"The party's goal is to win the right to express the hopes and
wishes of a large sector of the Egyptian people who want to see
Islamic law implemented peacefully," Ismail said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
Ismail, a lawyer who defends Islamic militants being tried for
anti-government activities, expressed hope that the party will be
legalized "to create an atmosphere of confidence between the
Islamic groups and the government."
</P>
<P>
It is doubtful that the government, which does not recognize
religious groups, will grant the permission. It has rejected a
similar request from a less-radical group on the grounds that its
political agenda resembled that of existing parties. All political
parties in Egypt are required to have government approval.
</P>
<P>
Among those who signed the petition and the party's political
manifesto are former militants or relatives of imprisoned members
of Egypt's two largest radical groups, al-Gamma al-Islamiya, or
the Islamic Group, and al-Jihad al-Islami, the Muslim Holy
Warriors.
</P>
<P>
Both groups led an insurgency aimed at toppling the secular
government and replacing it with strict Islamic rule. More than
1,200 people, mainly policemen and militants, were killed in the
violence that began in 1992 but has quieted down in recent years.
</P>
<P>
Many of those who signed the petition, including Ismail, spent
years in jail for participating in the 1981 assassination of
President Anwar Sadat or other violence. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
