<HEADLINE> S. Leone Rebel Leaders Play Down Differences </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, October 2 (Xinhua) -- Sierra Leone's main rebel leaders
Foday Sankoh and Johnny Koroma Saturday played down their
differences and reassured that they would go home to implement the
Lome peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
 Sankoh told a joint briefing in Liberia's capital Monrovia
before leaving for Sierra leone that they have put their
differences behind them, according to reports reaching here.
However, the two leaders did not specify their internal
differences.
</P>
<P>
"We are going to Freetown to help consolidate the peace and
contribute to the transformation of our society," he added.
</P>
<P>
"We have now agreed that enough time has been wasted and it's
high time that we return home and put this process on the road,"
said former military ruler Koroma after two days of talks with
Sankoh in Monrovia.
</P>
<P>
"We were able to clear any misunderstandings or disagreements
that were impeding the ongoing peace process," said Koroma.
</P>
<P>
He also paid tribute to the role of Liberia's president Charles
Taylor in bridging their differences.
</P>
<P>
"Sankoh and I have agreed that there will be no more war in
Sierra Leone. The war is now over and it is now time to jaw-jaw,"
he added.
</P>
<P>
In another latest development, the west African peace-keeping
force of ECOMOG has ordered all representatives of the factors
involved in Sierra Leone's crisis out of the capital Freetown for
one week to enable them to start disarmament exercise in the
country.
</P>
<P>
ECOMOG Field Commander Gabriel Kpamber said in a statement
released Friday that ECOMOG is demanding free and safe access to
every part of the country under the control of the rebels.
</P>
<P>
"This should be done with a view to paving a way for immediate
 construction of arms collection sites and demobilization centers
in designated locations all over Sierra Leone, " the statement
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
