<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ecuadoran Volcano Shows Activity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
QUITO, October 2 (Xinhua) -- Ecuador's Guagua Pichincha volcano
has already entered a phase of slow eruption with spewing of
ashes, lava and violent explosions in its crater.
</P>
<P>
The National Polytechnical School Geophysics Institute reported
Saturday that hot, incandescent rocks have been observed in the
dome, or hardened lava stopper of the crater, that rise because of
the pressure exerted by the magma toward the surface.
</P>
<P>
This phenomenon was observed Wednesday night by the crew of a
commercial airliner who saw a "red spot" in the crater of the
mountain 4,794 meters above sea level.
</P>
<P>
The Pichincha volcano has two main peaks, the active Guagua
Pichincha, 12 kilometers west of Ecuador's capital city of Quito,
and the inactive Rucu Pichincha, which stands as a natural barrier
between the volcano's crater and Quito.
</P>
<P>
Guagua Pichincha has been and is still an active volcano. It's
last major eruption was in 1660 and lasted nine days. Quito was
covered by 25 centimeters of ash and volcanic fragments. No one
was killed.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
