<HEADLINE> Zambian President Urges Africa to Develop Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, October 3 (Xinhua) -- Zambian President Frederick
Chiluba Sunday said it is impossible to fight the AIDS pandemic
and reduce poverty in a continent plagued by weak economies.
</P>
<P>
Chiluba made the remarks at the Lusaka International Airport
shortly before he left for the Victoria Falls town in Zimbabwe
where he would attend the 3rd Southern Africa International Dialog
(SAID).
</P>
<P>
The president, who described the summit as very important to
the African economies, would be among 14 other heads of state and
government scheduled to attend the conference whose focus would be
on the problem of HIV/AIDS and the growing level of poverty in
Africa.
</P>
<P>
He said it is impossible to talk about poverty alleviation or
HIV pandemic by third world countries at the moment because of the
huge money required to tackle the issues.
</P>
<P>
Chiluba said the meeting would also focus on how science and
technology could be utilized to maximize production of goods and
services in order to improve economic performance in Africa and
reduce its dependence on the West.
</P>
<P>
"I believe that third world countries could cooperate and make
their economies better and hence improve their trade thereby
translating into independence from the West," he said.
</P>
<P>
Chiluba said the wars that are going around in Africa could
only be minimized with bigger and stronger economies, because some
of the wars stemmed from bad sharing of the wealth or the lack of
it at all by the countries involved. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
