<HEADLINE> Iraq, Iran Ready to Expand Ties on U.N. Approvals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, October 3 (Xinhua) -- Iraq and Iran have expressed
readiness to expand bilateral ties within the framework of the
United Nations approvals.
</P>
<P>
Visiting Iraqi Minister of Industry and Minerals Adnan al-Ani
and Iranian Commerce Minister Mohammad Shariatmadar voiced the
readiness during the talks Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Exports of parmaceutical products, transit of goods via Iraq to
regional countries, and expansion of border trade especially
through border markets were among the major issues discussed by
the two ministers.
</P>
<P>
They also called for implementation of the signed trade
agreements between the two countries, the establishment of trade
centers in Tehran and Baghdad and the opening of new border
markets.
</P>
<P>
Al-Ani arrived here Thursday evening with a delegation to
attend the 25th Tehran trade fair.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has been under U.N. economic sanctions since 1990
following its invasion of Kuwait. But the U.N. has allowed Baghdad
to export limited amount of oil since 1996 to buy food, medicine
and other humanitarian goods for its 22 million people. 
</P>
