<HEADLINE> Malaysian PM Calls for Balance Between Development, Environment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, October 3 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Prime Minister
Mahathir Mohamad Sunday called upon the developing countries to
enhance construction projects and programs to enable greater
participation of the rural folk in socio-economic development.
</P>
<P>
A transport policy needs to strike a balance between three key
issues -- the environment, the economy and users' preferences, he
said in his speech at the opening of the week-long 21st World Road
Congress here, which was read out by Deputy Prime Minister
Abdullah Ahmad Badawi.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir said that roads and other models of transportation
represented the key to enhance quality of life.
</P>
<P>
He said the dilemma facing many developing countries is to
balance development and environment, adding that in Malaysia
sustainable development with the impending emphasis on the
protection of the environment has been given priority.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir said although the world subscribes to various
environmental declarations including the 1992 Rio summit where the
"rich" would contribute to the poor to prevent those countries
from cutting trees for development, the contribution from the rich
was not forthcoming.
</P>
<P>
He said that in Malaysia, adequate measures were taken to
minimize environmental damage in major development projects
including road construction.
</P>
<P>
The 21st World Road Congress, with its theme being "Is
Privatization of Road Infrastructure the Answer for Accelerated
Road Development in the 21st Century," was jointly organized by
the World Road Association and the Malaysian government, and has
attracted some 2,000 participants, including more than a dozen of
ministers, from some 90 countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
