<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> One Killed, 50 Injured in Strike in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, October 3 (Xinhua) -- One person was killed and about 50
others were injured in Bangladesh on Sunday during the
opposition-organized dawn-to-dusk countrywide hartal (destructive
strike).
</P>
<P>
One activist of the major opposition -- the Bangladesh
Nationalist Party (BNP) -- was gunned down in a clash between pro-
and anti-hartal activists in Sherpur district, about 150
kilometers north of here, reports reaching here said.
</P>
<P>
The three-hour battle at Sherpur town between supporters of the
opposition and anti-strike activists of the ruling Awami League
also left 20 persons injured, including one constable, a
superintendent of police was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Some 25 people were injured during the shutdown in northeastern
Netrakona town, about 140 km from Dhaka, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
Witnesses said some 50 opposition marchers were arrested by
police in the capital city.
</P>
<P>
The BNP-led opposition alliance, which also comprises the
Jatiya Party, the Jamaat-e-Islami and the Islami Oikya Jote
(Islamic Solidarity Front), enforced the strike to press home
their demands including the resignation of the government and
early parliamentary elections.
</P>
<P>
The government, on its part, enforced tight security in the
capital with a call for citizens to go to work as usual and bring
the vehicles on the streets, and the Awami League and its front
organizations brought out processions in Dhaka to protest the
nationwide strike.
</P>
<P>
However, despite the strong presence of police and
para-military Bangladesh Rifles, traffic was thin in the streets,
and only some rickshaws, mini-cabs and a few buses were seen
plying in the streets of the capital.
</P>
<P>
Almost all schools and shopping centers remained shut although
police authorities had earlier assured adequate security for
keeping shopping centers open.
</P>
<P>
The dawn-to-dust strike came two weeks after opposition parties
enforced a three-day work stoppage in mid-September as part of
their movement to unseat the government.
</P>
<P>
The opposition blamed the government of "inefficient, corrupt,
undemocratic and subservient to India," and the government denied
these charges. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
