<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ethiopia to Start Exporting Sugar Next Month </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, October 3 (Xinhua) -- Ethiopia will start
exporting surplus sugar in November this year, the first of its
kind in the history of the Horn of Africa country, the Capital
weekly reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Some 100,000 tons of sugar, worth 22 million U.S. dollars, are
expected to be exported by the end of June, 2000, the Ethiopian
Sugar Industry Support Center (ESISC) was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The total sugar production this year in Ethiopia was reported
to be 275,000 tons, much higher than last year's 175,000 tons.
</P>
<P>
Most of the sugar for export will come from the Finchaa Sugar
Factory's output, ESISC said.
</P>
<P>
The Finchaa Sugar Factory, the fourth of its kind in Ethiopia,
was inaugurated in April 1998 with an investment of 1.8 billion
birr (about 220 million U.S. dollars). It was designed to produce
85,000 tons of sugar a year.
</P>
<P>
Sugar export is expected to help diversify Ethiopia's economy
and reduce its dependence on coffee export, which currently
accounts for around 60 percent of foreign currency earnings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
