<DOCNO> XIE19991003.0062 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Oldest Catholic Church Reopens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 3 (Xinhua)-- Beijing's 300-year-old Xuanwumen
Catholic Church, which is believed to be the oldest Catholic
church in China, reopened this morning after a couple of months of
repairs.
</P>
<P>
This cathedral is the head of the Beijing Diocese. It was
begun by the Franciscan priest, Giovani da Montecorvino in 1605
and later enlarged by the Jesuit Adam Schall, in 1650. In 1904, it
was rebuilt after a major fire.
</P>
<P>
As the first Catholic Church in China, South Church (its former
name) has seen the unfolding of China's modern history and is a
rather valuable relic, according to Joseph Liu, the secretary-
general with the Beijing Catholic Church Administrative Commission.
</P>
<P>
But after centuries of wind, rain, and earthquakes, the
cathedral was in dire need of repairs, Liu says. Repairs were
delayed for years because of a lack of funds. At the beginning of
this year, the Beijing government took a look at the situation and
decided to appropriate 1.3 million yuan (149,000 U.S. dollars) for
major repairs.
</P>
<P>
The renovation project began in August and included interior
repairs, repairing the cross, and installing new windows, and the
old church has been given a complete facelift. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
