<DOCNO> XIE19991003.0063 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli-Palestinian Officials to Meet Again on Passage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, October 3 (Xinhua) -- The Israeli-Palestinian Safe
Passage Committee is scheduled to meet again Sunday evening to
iron out differences over the opening of the safe passage linking
Gaza Strip and the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Public Security Minister Shlomo Ben-Ami said the
Committee can settle the contentious issues concerning the opening
of the passage soon.
</P>
<P>
The passage will be opened on Sunday as scheduled but due to
some differences between the two sides, its opening has been
postponed, said the minister.
</P>
<P>
Israeli and Palestinian negotiators met at Neveh Ilan Hotel
near Jerusalem for more than five hours Saturday evening on the
opening of the passage.
</P>
<P>
Orit Messer-Harel, Spokeswoman of the Israeli Public Security,
announced after the meeting that the two sides decided to postpone
the opening of the route and they "agreed to meet in the coming
days to overcome the differences."
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued after midnight, Ben-Ami said he hoped the
two sides will reach an understanding soon based on two key
principles: security and sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
The two sides during their talks failed to narrow gaps over
which side should issue the magnetic security cards and where. And
they also disagreed over whether Israel is entitled to arrest
Palestinians suspected of security offenses as they use the
passage.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian negotiating team, led by Minister of Civil
Affairs Jamil Tarif, went to consult with Palestinian National
Authority Chairman Yasser Arafat after the talks broke up.
</P>
<P>
The passage, linking Gaza and the West Bank city of Hebron, has
to be opened October 1 under the Sharm El Sheikh peace deal signed
early September. But the opening has been postponed for two days
until Sunday by the Israeli side due to Israel's Jewish holiday.
</P>
</TEXT>
