<BODY>
<HEADLINE> GCC Naval Forces Launch Joint Drills in Qatar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, October 3 (Xinhua) -- Naval forces from the Gulf
Cooperation Council (GCC) states started their joint exercises
code-named "Solidarity Six" off the coast of Qatar in the Gulf on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
A Qatar naval official said the drills, which are scheduled to
run until October 15, are aimed at rehearsing joint operations in
repulsing foreign aggressions, and at testing the command and
control centers as well as the communication systems of the GCC
air forces.
</P>
<P>
The official said each of the GCC member states has sent one
ship and a group of frogmen to participate in the three-phase
maneuvers, according to the Kuwait News Agency.
</P>
<P>
The GCC joint marine drills, which were first launched in
1984, are held every two years in a GCC state.
</P>
<P>
The GCC states usually hold joint war games with the major
western powers with which they have signed defense cooperation
agreements.
</P>
<P>
The GCC, a regional political and economic alliance established
in 1981, comprises Bahrain, Kuwait, Oman, Qatar, Saudi Arabia and
the United Arab Emirates. 
</P>
</TEXT>
