<HEADLINE> More Opportunities Created in HK to Know China's Mainland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 3 (Xinhua) -- Celebration activities should
be organized to have the Hong Kong people to know more about China
's mainland, said Anson Chan, administrative secretary of the Hong
Kong Special Administrative Region (HKSAR), on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
"I like the way the carnival is organized to represent the
theme of the history and development of modern China so that
participants can learn more about China while enjoying themselves,
" the secretary said at a garden carnival in celebration of the
50th anniversary of the founding of the People's Republic of China
sponsored by the organizations of public servants Sunday morning.
</P>
<P>
She stressed that it is of great significance to have more
activities initiated to demonstrate the dramatic progress China
has made over the past half century.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to efforts in the past 50 years, China has been turned
from a poor, closed agricultural country into one with the fastest
economic growth in the world, she said, adding that China has also
played an important role on the world political stage.
</P>
<P>
According to the World Bank, she said, by the year 2020, China
will become one of the three world's largest economic powers. "The
dramatic achievements it has made is a great encouragement to us,"
she added.
</P>
<P>
The ties between Hong Kong and the mainland have been as close
as lips and teeth, she noted. Apart from serving as a bridge for
China's foreign trade, Hong Kong is an important partner of the
mainland in the economic development, scientific research and
exchange of talents, she added.
</P>
<P>
Looking into the future, Hong Kong will continue to do its best
in China's reforms and modernization, she noted.
</P>
<P>
There are more and more opportunities for Hong Kong public
servants to make contact with officials in the mainland, she said.
The SAR government has in recent years launched a variety of
activities to strengthen the coordination and exchanges in all
fields to promote a mutual development, she added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
