<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Women Representation Expected in Ethiopian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, October 3 (Xinhua) -- An Ethiopian woman leader
has urged all parties in the country to field more and deserving
women candidates to run for the nation-wide elections in May 2000.
</P>
<P>
The Ethiopian Herald Sunday quoted Woizero Haile-Michael, head
of the Women's Affairs in the Prime Minister's Office, as saying
that political parties must provide women candidates with special
support.
</P>
<P>
Woizero said despite the fact that over 50 percent of the
electorate constitute women, the number of women candidates for
the next elections is very low because of their fear to engage in
politics and the mistaken outlook of the society towards women.
</P>
<P>
She called on political parties to emulate the country's
consitutional provision that advocates affirmative action for
women, and embrace such a provision in their programs, not only
for the benefit of elections but to guarantee women's
participation in all areas of endeavor.
</P>
<P>
She said that her office was preparing to provide the necessary
support to women, with a view to raising women representation in
the House of Peoples' Representatives from the current seven to 15
percent and that of the state council from eight to 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
According to local press, some 58 political parties across
Ethiopia have announced that they will participate in the national
and regional elections due on May 14, 2000, the second of its kind
since August 1995. 
</P>
</TEXT>
