<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Police Probe Alleged Thefts at Buckingham Palace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 3 (Xinhua) -- British police were investigating
a series of alleged thefts of royal treasures from Buckingham
Palace, Queen Elizabeth's London residence, local newspapers
reported on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
A Scotland Yard spokeswoman gave no details of the
investigations, but played down a report in the News of the World
that "fabulous jewels and heirlooms" had been looted, including a
necklace belonging to Princess Anne.
</P>
<P>
"It's not an accurate story," the spokeswoman said, adding that
the items which were allegedly stolen were "items of intrinsic
value, but not highly valuable."
</P>
<P>
"They were of no personal or sentimental value to any member of
the Royal Family," she said.
</P>
<P>
The News of the World newspaper said the haul included an
ornament given to Queen Elizabeth during a state visit, fine wines,
silver cutlery and clothes created by top international designers.
</P>
<P>
"Private apartments have been systematically ransacked," it
said, adding that the value of goods looted stood at tens of
thousands of pounds (dollars).
</P>
<P>
The Sunday Times said stolen goods also included an Olympic tie-
pin given to Princess Anne when she competed in the 1976 Montreal
Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
More than 800 palace staff are expected to be questioned about
the thefts, carried out over several weeks. They are believed to
be the work of insiders with access to private offices and
apartments.
</P>
<P>
Five years ago, thieves broke into heir-to-the-throne Prince
Charles's apartments at St. James Palace, making away with several
sets of pens, tie-pins, watches and brooches of historic and
sentimental value.
</P>
<P>
In the same year, a former Buckingham Palace porter pleaded
guilty to stealing a 350,000 pound (580,000 U.S. dollars) 17th
century painting from the royal collection. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
