<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Modern Locomotives to Be Operational on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, October 3 (Xinhua) -- The Ethio-Djibouti Railway
Company has imported two modern locomotives made in France at a
cost of 4.9 million birr (600,000 U.S. dollars), the Capital
weekly reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The purchase was financed by the French Development Agency in
Ethiopia as part of the 56 million French Francs (about nine
million U.S. dollars) grant the agency allocated for the
rehabilitation of the railway.
</P>
<P>
The 102-year-old railway company, jointly owned by Ethiopia
and Djibouti, currently has 14 locomotives with a total capacity
of transporting 30,000 tons of goods per month.
</P>
<P>
According to Solomon Eshetu, planning and research head of the
railway company, the imported locomotives have 300 horsepower each
with the capacity to pull four wagons.
</P>
<P>
The new locomotives will speed up the rehabilitation work that
is scheduled to be finalized by the year 2003, Solomon said.
</P>
</TEXT>
