<HEADLINE> Northern Irish Police Chief Warns of New Terror Threat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 3 (Xinhua) -- Northern Ireland's chief police
officer warned on Sunday that dissident republican guerrilla
groups posed a growing threat of violence in the province.
</P>
<P>
Ronnie Flanagan, head of the Royal Ulster Constabulary, said
the republican splinter groups were attracting new recruits.
</P>
<P>
He also threatened to resign if Britain ordered him to cut the
size of his force, as a result of a recently completed review of
policing in Northern Ireland, before the threat from dissident
guerrilla groups was reduced.
</P>
<P>
Flanagan said in a BBC interview that the Roman Catholic
republican splinter groups had the "firm intention" of engaging in
violence, but had been deterred by police and the army.
</P>
<P>
But there was no evidence that the Irish Republican Army was
involved in the threat of renewed violence, Flanagan said.
</P>
<P>
He insisted his force must remain strong enough to protect the
public from any future resumption of guerrilla violence.
</P>
<P>
The policing report by former Hong Kong governor Chris Patten
has angered Protestants and police officers with its suggestion
that the Royal Ulster Constabulary's full-time strength be reduced
from 13,000 to 7,500. 
</P>
