<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, October 3 (Xinhua) -- Kenyans Paul Tergat and Tegla
Loroupe took the men's and women's world half-marathon titles at
Palermo, Sicily, on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Tergat, a five-time world cross country champion, almost threw
away victory in the closing meters when he bumped into a race
official who went on to the course to point Tergat toward the
finish line.
</P>
<P>
Yet Tergat still managed to take the title with a time of one
hour, one minute and 50 seconds. Ramaala of South Africa finished
second with the same time, followed by Tesfaye Jifar of Ethiopia
in the third place with one second behind.
</P>
<P>
Tegla Loroupe took the women's crown for the third consecutive
time.
</P>
<P>
Loroupe, who broke her own world record for the marathon last
weekend in Berlin, led from the start. She was timed at one hour,
8 minutes and 48 seconds.
</P>
<P>
Mizuki Noguchi of Japan was second in 1:09:12, followed by
Catherine Ndereba of Kenya in 1:09:23.
</P>
<P>
The men's team title was taken by South Africa which had three
runners in the top 10 finishers. The women's team title went to
Kenya. 
