<HEADLINE> Pak to Wait US Action on Removal of Sanctions: FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, October 3 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan's position on the
Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty (CTBT) has remained unchanged and it
would wait for the U.S. Congress action with regard to removal of
sanctions before taking decision on signing of the treaty.
</P>
<P>
This was stated Sunday by Pakistani Foreign Minister Sartaj
Aziz at a press conference on return from a 12-day trip to the
United Nations and the United States.
</P>
<P>
"There is no change in our position stated by Prime Minister
Nawaz Sharif at last year's session of the U.N. General Assembly
session," Aziz said.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Sharif told the world body that Pakistan would
accede to CTBT in an atmosphere free of coercion and pressure.
</P>
<P>
"That action has not been taken, the pre-requisite has not been
met," Aziz said, referring to lifting of the discriminatory
sanctions imposed by the United States against Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
Aziz, who met with U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright
and several U.S. law-makers during his visit, said Washington did
raise the issue of signing of CTBT with him.
</P>
<P>
"They told me that the action is now with the U.S. Congress,"
Aziz said, adding that "I don't know how adequate that action will
be, but we will wait for the outcome of that action." 
</P>
</TEXT>
