<HEADLINE> Pakistani, Indian PMs May Meet in November </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, October 3 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Foreign Minister
Sartaj Aziz Sunday indicated that Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif may
meet his Indian counterpart Atal Bihari Vajpayee on the sidelines
of the Commonwealth Summit in the South African city of Durban in
November.
</P>
<P>
Replying to questions during a press conference held here, Aziz
said, "Talks should start as soon as possible. One opportunity
will be in Durban at the Commonwealth Summit in mid November,"
stressing that the dialogue should start "in whatever the way".
Another chance for a possible meeting of the prime ministers from
the two hostile neighbors will be the South Asian Association for
Regional Cooperation (SAARC) Summit in Katmandu, capital of Nepal,
scheduled for November 26, according to Aziz.
The prime ministers' meetings will mark the resumption of stalled
bilateral talks between the two South Asian countries.
</P>
<P>
Sharif and Vajpayee held a meeting in Pakistan's eastern city
of Lahore in February this year. However, the foreign secretary
level talks could not be resumed as agreed due to the collapse of
Vajpayee government and the eruption of military conflicts in the
disputed area of Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
The two arch-rivals have been under international pressure to
resume dialogue for the peaceful settlement of bilateral disputes,
especially the long-standing Kashmir issue. 
</P>
