<HEADLINE> 16 Killed, 22 Injured in Road Accidents in Egypt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, October 3 (Xinhua) -- Sixteen people were killed and 22
others injured in two separate road accidents in northern Egypt,
the national Al-Ahram daily reported on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
One accident took place Saturday on the Cairo-Alexandria Desert
Road in the governorate of Gharbia, 80 kilometers north of the
capital, the Arabic-language newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
A tractor ran into a truck which was carrying 35 people of one
family on their way back home, killing eight of them and injuring
22 others.
</P>
<P>
The other accident occurred also on Saturday in Suez, 120
kilometers east of Cairo, when two cars crashed into each other,
claiming eight lives.
</P>
<P>
Investigations into the causes of the accidents are underway,
the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
Road accidents are common in Egypt due to over speed, poor road
conditions and neglect of traffic rules and regulations. Official
estimates put the annual death toll at nearly 6,000 people and
injuries at 30,000.
</P>
<P>
A government committee is looking into the rising number of
fatalities on Egyptian roads, especially rural roads, which local
medias have dubbed "roads of death." 
</P>
</TEXT>
