<HEADLINE> Kenya not Poorest Country: President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, October 3 (Xinhua) -- Kenya is not among the least
developing countries,  Kenyan President Daniel arap Moi said
Saturday while talking about the omission of Kenya from the list
of countries whose debts are to be written off by the United
States.
</P>
<P>
The Herald newspaper Sunday quoted Moi as saying Kenya only
owes the United States 58 million U.S. dollars in bilateral aids
and another 67, 000 dollars in commercial loans.
</P>
<P>
What Kenya needs from the United States is preferential trade
and investments, Moi said when addressing a fund-raising function
for a high- school.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Kenyan Foreign Minister Bonaya Godana said that
54945
Kenya did not meet the criteria for a 100 percent debt write-off.
</P>
<P>
Kenya has neither been at war nor been unable to service its
external debt obligations and these are factors that were
considered in giving countries debt reprieve, Godana said.
</P>
<P>
If Kenya had received a debt reprieve, it would be denied
access to credit "especially from the Japanese government who is
our principal donors" , he said.
</P>
<P>
"It was not in our interests to push for a debt write-off
because there are some countries which spend up to 108 percent of
their total revenue on repaying debts owed by their governments,"
the minister said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
