<HEADLINE> Exporting Stray Orphans Probed in Zambia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, October 3 (Xinhua) -- A suspected orphan smuggler in
northern Zambia is being probed, Sunday Mail reported.
</P>
<P>
The resident in Kitwe is allegedly exporting stray orphans to
some unnamed European countries, according to the local newspaper.
</P>
<P>
Moses Sampa, out-going community schools coordinator of the
District Orphans and Vulnerable Children's Committee (DOVC), was
quoted as saying that he has received the report from reliable
sources.
</P>
<P>
Sampa, one of the first African missionaries of Hope for
Vulnerable Children in Africa, said the suspect is obtaining
passports for the children.
</P>
<P>
He said everything possible will be done to come up with
concrete evidence.
</P>
<P>
DOVC chairman C'ome Munsha said he is aware of the report and
promised to take it up with Kitwe District police chief Martin
Mshanga.
</P>
<P>
Sources in the city said the children being exported could
either be used for sex or cheap labor in industry.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile the United Methodist Church has pledged to work with
DOVC in alleviating the plight of street children in the city
which is believed to have the highest number of vulnerable
children. 
</P>
