<HEADLINE> Tanzania Calls for Second Africa Liberation to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, October 3 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania has called for a
second liberation in the African continent to make it a meaningful
participant in the new world trade and investment globalization.
</P>
<P>
President Benjamin Mkapa made the remarks Saturday in a speech
read by Tanzanian Prime Minister Frederick Sumaye at the Third
Herbert Chitepo Memorial Lecture held at University of Zimbabwe in
Harare.
</P>
<P>
"Africa has jumped on the globalization bandwagon unprepared,"
Mkapa said.
</P>
<P>
Since Africa was so divided and weak, the courage to protest
and stand up for the interests of its people has diminished and
become unfashionable, he added.
</P>
<P>
"We all agree that we cannot escape from globalization and we
should not try to. But we need to stand up for our interests," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Mkapa said that the biggest challenge for Africa was how it can
build, develop and sustain its capacity to be a meaningful player
in the globalizing world.
</P>
<P>
He cherished the united and spirited fight for a new
international economic order by the then Non-Aligned Movement and
G77 in the 1970s, saying these were instrumental in pursuit of
that just demand.
</P>
<P>
"For once we promoted an economic agenda for the South on a
global scale, the Western industrialized countries had to work
extra to scuttle that agenda," the president observed.
</P>
<P>
Speaking on debts, he said Tanzania has spent twice as much
money servicing its debt than it has spent on education and
health.
</P>
<P>
Mkapa said that despite the unbearable debt burden, African
governments do not seem to be united in demanding deeper, quicker
and broader debt relief and cancellation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
