<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Missile Interceptor Passes Crucial Test </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 2 (Xinhua) -- The United States on Saturday
conducted a test of national missile defense system which
intercepted and destroyed an unarmed missile on a 25,600-kph
collision course over the Pacific.
</P>
<P>
An unarmed missile lifted off from Vandenberg Air Force Base in
California. A "kill vehicle", which lifted off from the Kwajalein
test range in the South Pacific about 21 minutes later,
intercepted and collided with the target above the ocean.
</P>
<P>
"It was a successful intercept," said Sheryl Irwin, a
spokeswoman for the U.S. Department of Defense. "It did everything
it was supposed to do, and it did it perfectly."
</P>
<P>
This was the first test of the "kill vehicle" missile's ability
to destroy a target by smashing into it. Neither missile carried
an explosive.
</P>
<P>
Two more tests are scheduled before a June 2000 deployment
readiness review by the Pentagon and a presidential decision on
initial deployment, expected shortly thereafter.
</P>
<P>
Deployment of a possible 20 interceptors in Alaska by 2001, if
approved, would put the United States in violation of the Anti-
Ballistic Missile treaty with Russia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
