<HEADLINE> African Regional leaders to Discuss Partnerships </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, October 3 (Xinhua) -- The Third Southern Africa
International Dialogue (SAID) conference opens Sunday in the
resort town of Victoria Falls, Zimbabwe, to chart the course for
smart partnerships within the region, Zimbabwe News Agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
About 13 heads of state and government andover 400 businessmen
from the Southern African Development Community (SADC) region,
together with delegates from other parts of the world, are
expected to attend the four-day conference to seek ways for
enhancing regional economic growth.
</P>
<P>
In his welcome message to the delegates, Zimbabwean President
Robert Mugabe called on all countries in the region to pursue
economic development through the promotion of peace, political
stability and the creation of smart partnerships.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe said this year's dialogue should focus on the region's
greatest challenge of working out strategies for empowering the
indigenous majorities who have been victims of socio-economic
inequalities.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the hope that the conference would come up with
practical measures, which will result in the formation of business
linkages in many economic sectors in the region.
</P>
<P>
"All of us in the region have come to realize that the ideals
of empowerment and the search for greater investment, growth and
development can, and indeed should be harmonized. After all,
empowerment policies are only realizable under conditions of
growth. This is why we urge big businesses -- local and
international -- to realize that the quest for empowerment and the
 pursuit of profit need not conflict," he said.
</P>
<P>
During the four-day dialogue under the theme "Economic
Empowerment Through Smart Partnership", the participants are
expected to deliberate on technology and business development
opportunities, the role of business in economic empowerment for
smart partnership projects and the social agenda for economic
empowerment.
</P>
<P>
SAID is a platform for debating regional economic issues and is
modeled along the lines of Malaysia's Langkawi International
Dialogue.
</P>
<P>
This year's session is the third after the inaugural dialogue
held in Kasane, Botswana in 1997 and the second held in
Swakopmund, Namibia last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
