<DOCNO> XIE19991003.0107 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: India's Lok Sabha Polls Enter Final Phase </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, October 3 (Xinhua) -- India's long-drawn 13th Lok
Sabha election entered the fifth and final phase Sunday in 118
constituencies spread over 11 states in the country amid tight
security measures.
</P>
<P>
More than 130 million voters are eligible to decide the
electoral fortunes of 1,087 candidates, including Prime Minister
Atal Bihari Vajpayee and Congress President Sonia Gandhi.
</P>
<P>
As the final phase of polling began Sunday morning, the country
is witnessing a clash of political heavyweights in Amethi and
Lucknow Lok Sabha constituencies in Uttar Pradesh, where Sonia
Gandhi and Vajpayee are in the fray.
</P>
<P>
For Congress President Sonia Gandhi, her victory in both Amethi
and Bellary Lok Sabha constituencies appears to be crucial for her
survival, as a defeat in any of these constituencies could
establish the stamp of a "foreigner being rejected by Indian
voters."
</P>
<P>
On the eve of the polls Saturday, The Pioneer, one of India's
leading newspapers, predicted the BJP-led National Democratic
Alliance (NDA) will have a comfortable lead in the 13th Lok Sabha
election.
</P>
<P>
An exclusive survey commissioned by The Pioneer said that the
BJP-led NDA is set to cross the 300 mark while the Congress and
its allies will obtain 165 seats. Other parties will get 71 seats.
</P>
<P>
The survey forecast 41 percent vote for the BJP and allies, a
gain of 3.3 percent. The Congress and its allies are expected to
secure 35.4 percent of the vote, a jump of six percent over the
last election.
</P>
<P>
The survey (post-poll in most constituencies and pre-poll in
some) was conducted by the Research and Development Initiative in
the last week of September with representative sample of 80 Lok
Sabha constituencies covering 16,800 eligible voters.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, buoyed up by reports of a turnaround in its fortunes
in Uttar Pradesh and some other states, the Congress has come to
the conclusion that it would emerge as the single largest party in
the 13th Lok Sabha.
</P>
<P>
Congress spokesman Kapil Sibal said Saturday, "There is no
doubt that the Congress will form the government." He also did
not rule out the possibility of the Congress forming a coalition
government.
</P>
<P>
However, Home Minister L.K. Advani, who is also the BJP
campaign chairman, attempted to demolish this "myth" by insisting
that while the NDA would get a clear majority, the honor of being
the single largest party would go to the BJP, and not to the
Congress.
</P>
<P>
The latter, as he put it, did not have "a ghost of chance."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
