<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Ease Control on Silver Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 3 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese government has
decided to lift the decades-old ban on free trading and pricing of
silver in three months in a bid to boost demand and solve the
surplus problem.
</P>
<P>
The deregulation is a prelude to a similar market-driven
program for gold, today's Business Weekly quoted an official from
the Gold Economic Development Research Center as saying.
</P>
<P>
However, only a few domestic dealers will be granted access to
the silver market after the government's deregulation, according
to Liu Shan'an, deputy-director of the center.
</P>
<P>
There is no accurate timetable for the government to open
silver and gold markets to overseas traders.
</P>
<P>
Trading and pricing of gold and silver have been under the
monopoly control of the People's Bank of China, the country's
central bank, since the early days of the People's Republic.
</P>
<P>
Insiders said the pilot silver exchange markets will likely be
established in a non-ferrous metals wholesale market on January 1,
2000, in Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
Only domestic dealers will be allowed to make spot silver
transactions using the renminbi currency.
</P>
<P>
Silver exports will remain under the control of the central
bank. Now, any company that wishes to handle exports of silver are
required to get a licence from the central bank.
</P>
<P>
The State Economic and Trade Commission will implement a quota
system on silver exports beginning next year.
</P>
<P>
China's silver output stood at 1,300 tons last year. But the
domestic market could only absorb 600 tons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
