<HEADLINE> Rains to Continue in Central America </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN JOSE, October 2 (Xinhua) -- Heavy rains that have killed
almost 60 people and caused 25,000 U.S. dollars of damage to
Central America are to continue next week, meteorological
forecasts said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Experts of the Guatemala Meteorology Institute said two low
pressure systems in the Pacific and the Atlantic oceans have
caused the torrential rains in the isthmus.
</P>
<P>
The bad weather has caused 17 deaths in Honduras, 16 in
Guatemala, nine in El Salvador, nine in Nicaragua and six in Costa
Rica, civil protection authorities of these countries reported.
</P>
<P>
The number of people suffering damage because of the floods
totaled 25,125, with 11,520 in Honduras, 7,000 in El Salvador, 3,
130 in Nicaragua and 3,475 in Costa Rica.
</P>
<P>
Floods caused by the intense rains have affected road traffic,
destroyed houses and cut power and telephone lines in the region.
</P>
<P>
Central America was hit by hurricane Mitch in October and
November of 1998, which killed 10,000 people and caused billions
of dollars in material losses. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
