<HEADLINE> Myanmar CRPP Condemns Embassy Seizure in Bangkok </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, October 3 (Xinhua) -- The Committee Representing the
People's Parliament (CRPP) of Myanmar, mainly formed by the
opposition National League for Democracy (NLD), Saturday condemned
the seizure of the Myanmar embassy in Bangkok and the taking of
hostages by Myanmar armed men on Friday.
</P>
<P>
"Such acts are contrary to the principles which the CRPP and
the NLD are constantly defending in the name of justice, human
rights and peace," the CRPP said in a statement released here
Saturday evening.
</P>
<P>
"We deeply appreciate the decision of the Thai government to
reject the use of force and applaud the courage and diplomatic
skills of the deputy foreign minister (Sukhumbhand Paribatra),"
the statement said.
</P>
<P>
"We would like to draw the attention of the world to the fact
that this act of violence at the Burmese (Myanmar) embassy in
Bangkok is an effect of the many acts of injustice and cruelty
repeatedly perpetrated by the military regime in Burma (Myanmar).
Violence breeds violence," the statement added.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, according to Saturday's government statement, the
armed men, which had stormed the Myanmar embassy in Bangkok, left
the embassy compound to an unknown destination with two
helicopters provided by the Thai authorities after negotiations
between them on that day at 1 p.m. Bangkok time. The incident
ended peacefully.
</P>
<P>
The government Information Sheet said that the Thai authorities
are now questioning those who were held hostage for further
information, adding that no one has been hurt during the incident.
</P>
<P>
The Myanmar government warned that "it is important to make
these criminals realize that no matter under what pretext or
disguise it might have been staged, the peace loving people of the
world community will not tolerate the criminal and the terrorist
activities they have committed."
</P>
<P>
Five armed men with AK (47) rifles, who are all Myanmar
students living in Thailand, stormed the Myanmar embassy in
Bangkok at 10:50 a.m. local time on Friday and held the embassy
staff and their families together with a number of foreigners.
</P>
<P>
A total of 34 hostages have been reportedly freed from the
Myanmar embassy Saturday afternoon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
