<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wilson Hails Wednesday Courage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 2 (Xinhua) -- Sheffield Wednesday manager Danny
Wilson hailed his side's courage following their five-star
Hillsborough performance against Wimbledon at English premier
league match on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The Wednesday players produced an electrifying display, none
more so than Belgian international striker Gilles de Bilde.
</P>
<P>
De Bilde was on the score sheet twice in a 5-1 rout of
Wimbledon as the Owls finally brought an end to the worst league
start in their history.
</P>
<P>
There were also goals for Wim Jonk, Petter Rudi and Gerald
Sibon, with only John Hartson replying for the visitors.
</P>
<P>
But this was a performance full of commitment and heart, one
which Wilson had long been demanding from his players and while
the Wednesday boss was rightly proud of his side, he also warned
they are not yet out of the woods.
</P>
<P>
With Wednesday still propping up the Premiership, Wilson said:
"This was a terrific win.
</P>
<P>
"I said to the lads that it took a hell of a lot of courage to
play like that today, particularly given the crisis we are in.
</P>
<P>
"But I don't think there will be a better result up and down
the country over the next few weeks because of our situation and
given the pressure we are under.
</P>
<P>
"But we mustn't get carried away with just one win, although
from our point of view this sets us up to go forward.
</P>
<P>
"But we are still bottom of the league. I know the fans will
think we have turned the corner, but there's still a lot of work
to do," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
