<HEADLINE> IOC Approves New Sports for Salt Lake Olympics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, October 2 (Xinhua) -- The International Olympic
Committee approved on Saturday to add both skeleton and women's
bobsled to the competitive agenda for the 2002 Winter Games.
</P>
<P>
Skeleton is a sport in which an athlete rides a sled head-first
down an ice track.
</P>
<P>
The IOC executive board also approved the addition of men's and
women's 1,500-meter races in short-track speedskating, men's and
women's cross-country ski events, and men's combined sprints in
Nordic Combined.
</P>
<P>
The action came a day before the Salt Lake Organizing Committee
makes a presentation to the IOC board.
</P>
<P>
Salt Lake organizers had asked for approval of the new sports
and events at the IOC session in Seoul, South Korea, in June. But
the IOC said then it needed more information from international
federations to make sure the sports met the requirements for
inclusion in the games. 
</P>
</TEXT>
