<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Property Sector Firms, Recovery Needs Time </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, October 3 (Xinhua) -- Southeast Asia's property markets
have shown signs of renewed life in recent months, but lower
prices, higher vacancy rates and falling profits in much of the
region indicate a slower recovery.
</P>
<P>
Since the beginning of this year, a low interest rate
environment and the faster-than-expected regional economic
recovery have eased the crisis in the property sector. Singapore,
the Philippines and Malaysia have seen residential markets
improving in recent months.
</P>
<P>
Filinvest Land, a Philippine firm engaged in affordable
middle-income housing, reported a 7.6 percent drop in net profit
in the first half of the year on a year earlier, but said that
sales reservations were 96 percent higher than the first half of
1998.
</P>
<P>
In Singapore, many property companies have started to return to
profitability, mainly due to a steady recovery in home prices
since the market touched bottom last year.
</P>
<P>
DBS Land, Singapore's major play in the property sector,
reported in July a 174 percent surge in its interim profit.
</P>
<P>
"I think quite a few companies will return to black. But
whether they will be as astounding and spectacular in their
turnaround as DBS Land remains to be seen," said Yeo Wei Kwong,
analyst at Fraser Securities.
</P>
<P>
Lower interest rates, coupled with a robust economic recovery,
have fueled rises in residential sales in Southeast Asia in the
first half of the year.
</P>
<P>
In the past year, short-term interest rates in Malaysia,
Thailand, Indonesia and the Philippines have been cut by 7.3
percentage points on average. The lower cost of bank loans has
encouraged people to buy homes.
</P>
<P>
But economists said the better-than-expected economic
performance in the region is a major factor which boosted consumer
confidence.
</P>
<P>
Last year, most Southeast Asian nations experienced a severe
economic recession, with the region's gross domestic product (GDP)
contracting by 6.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
This year, however, all Southeast Asian countries are expected
to see positive growth. According to a revised forecast by the
Asian Development Bank in September, Singapore's GDP would grow 5
percent this year. The Philippines, Thailand, Malaysia and
Indonesia are also expected to achieve a 2-3 percent GDP growth
this year.
</P>
<P>
With a low interest rate environment and a real economic
turnaround, the property sector could see significant improvements
in the later part of the year, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
But the huge amount of non-performing loans extended by
Southeast Asian banks to the property sector is the major cause of
the two-year-old financial crisis, and the sector has been hit
hardest during the crisis with a steep slide of prices and a high
vacancy rate.
</P>
<P>
The full recovery in Southeast Asia is likely to take some
years because of over-supply and huge debts owed by property
companies, according to dealers.
</P>
<P>
In Thailand, the battered sector could take two to three years
to fully recover due to a sharp imbalance between supply and
demand, said Mana Jiranapakul, senior associate director of a
property management group in Thailand.
</P>
<P>
"My opinion is that it should take two to three years to see
the market pick up," he said.
</P>
<P>
In the Philippines, over-supply and intense competition in the
office and high-end residential segments, fund problems for
low-end housing would also delay a fully recovery.
</P>
<P>
A large supply to come through in both the office and high-end
residential segments will take 12-18 months, with vacancy rates
picking up for segments in 2000, said Edgardo del Rosario, deputy
head of research at Salomon Smith Barney.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia's problem is also very serious. It is reported that
some 11 million square feet of Kuala Lumpur office space, or 23.6
percent of the total, are currently vacant.
</P>
<P>
Besides, Malaysia's developers borrowed big to build their
projects. If they cannot make money, they cannot service their
loans, which account for 25 percent of the financial system's
total lending.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, economists are calling on Southeast Asian
governments to make more efforts to revive the property sector.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
