<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italian Cyclist Fails Doping Test </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, October 2 (Xinhua) -- Italy cyclist Simone Lo Vano has
failed a joint blood and urine test and was unable to compete in
the world championships next week, ANSA news agency reported on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Lo Vanuo, a time trial specialist, was the reigning national
champion at under 23 and world junior champion in 1996.
</P>
<P>
No details were available for the test, which forms part of a
national anti-doping campaign, checks the red corpuscle count in
the blood and the amount of creatine in urine.
</P>
<P>
The move comes four months after national cycling hero Marco
Pantani was prevented from starting the penultimate stage of the
Tour of Italy after the race leader failed an identical blood test.
</P>
<P>
A blood test failure is usually linked with use of the banned
drug EPO, which increases a rider's resistance to fatigue,
although Pantani has strenuously denied the charge of doping.
</P>
<P>
Creatine is a naturally-occurring substance which improves
muscle performance, but whose levels can be artificially boosted
by taking it in concentrated tablet form. 
</P>
</TEXT>
