<HEADLINE> Seven People Killed in Coach Crash in Italy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, October 2 (Xinhua) -- Seven people were killed and some
30 injured Saturday when their coach hit the side of a tunnel on a
motor-way near Genoa in northwest Italy.
</P>
<P>
According to police reports issued Saturday evening, the coach
left the small town of Castel Madama, 25 kilometers east of Rome,
at 2:30 a.m. local time carrying some 40 people who were heading
for Turin to attend a wedding.
</P>
<P>
The accident happened at 6:15 a.m., when the coach hit the
right side of the entrance to a two-kilometer-long tunnel,
crashing through safety barriers and sending a number of
passengers flying through the coach windows.
</P>
<P>
The owner-driver of the coach, Vincenzo Salviani, who was among
the victims, is believed to have fallen asleep at the wheel just
before entering the tunnel and slamming into the tunnel wall,
causing the coach to overturn.
</P>
<P>
On Saturday afternoon, 10 of the people injured in the accident
were reported in critical condition in hospitals in and around
Genoa.
</P>
<P>
Six children, aged between three and 11, who were aboard the
coach, were hospitalized with injuries. One 11-year-old girl was
said to be in serious condition with fractures and contusions.
</P>
<P>
A woman passenger hospitalized in Lavagna, near Genoa, reported
that she had seen the driver nodding off just seconds before the
accident.  
</P>
</TEXT>
