<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Spends Heavily on Earthquake Resistance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 3 (Xinhua) -- China had spent 1.4 billion yuan
(168 million U.S. dollars) on earthquake resistance before the end
of 1997, the Business Weekly today quoted an official with the
Ministry of Construction as saying.
</P>
<P>
Qu Qi, division chief of the ministry's earthquake resistance
office, said that China has placed emphasis on earthquake
resistance since the devastating 1976 Tangshan earthquake which
killed more than 200,000 people.
</P>
<P>
His remarks came in the wake of disastrous earthquakes that
have occurred in Turkey, Greece and China's Taiwan island within
the past several months.
</P>
<P>
The National Code for the Seismic Design of Buildings (GBJ11-89)
, which was effective since 1989, required that buildings should
not be damaged by minor tremors, should be repairable after medium
ones, and should not crumble because of major ones, Qu said.
</P>
<P>
In Beijing, permanent buildings and structures are required to
withstand tremors up to magnitude 8.
</P>
<P>
Construction companies should apply for approval from local
construction authorities to start a high-rise construction project,
and ask the ministry-approved committee of seismic experts to
examine designs and evaluate the overall anti-quake capacities.
</P>
<P>
Sources with the Ministry of Construction said China's high-
rise construction has mushroomed in recent years in the urban
areas. The country was in an active earthquake period during the
time of the Ninth Five-Year Plan (1996-2000).
</P>
<P>
China is revising the GBJ11-89 code to help disseminate
technological advances and experiences gained in resisting
earthquakes that have been accumulated during the past decades, Qu
said.
</P>
<P>
About 600 earthquakes measuring magnitude 6 or above have been
recorded in China during this century, killing at least 550,000
people. This is more than half the total of quake casualties in
the world during the period. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991003.0150 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Colombia Reports Falls in International Reserves </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTAFE DE BOGOTA, October 2 (Xinhua) -- Colombia's
international reserves dropped to 7.859 billion U.S. dollars at
the beginning of October after speculation against the peso in the
week preceding the elimination of the exchange band.
</P>
<P>
A report of the Republic Bank released on Saturday said that
this level of reserves is 415.4 million dollars less than one
month before.
</P>
<P>
There were strong attacks against the peso in the five market
working days between September 20 and 24, forcing the central bank
to spend its reserves to maintain the dollar price within the
limits of the exchange band.
</P>
<P>
The central bank's board of directors determined on September
25 to suppress the exchange band mechanism starting last Monday
and to let the value of the dollar fluctuate.
</P>
<P>
The peso recovered 0.225 percent of its value at the close of
the week, closing Friday in the interbank market at 1,990 pesos
per dollar, against 1,994.49 pesos one week ago. 
</P>
</TEXT>
