<HEADLINE> Colombia Urges U.S. to Assist in Anti-Drug War </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTAFE DE BOGOTA, October 2 (Xinhua) -- Commander of the
Colombian armed forces General Fernando Tapias on Saturday urged
the United States to provide assistance to the fight against drug-
trafficking in his country.
</P>
<P>
"If the U.S. wanted, it could see drug trafficking end in two
or three years. What we are asking for is to do it," Tapias told
the press before leaving for Washington on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Tapias said that despite the U.S. cooperation with Colombia in
the war against drugs, illegal crops have gone from 30,000 to 100,
000 hectares in the last five years.
</P>
<P>
The general said that some 1,500 people, in addition to 1,000
members of the armed forces, die every year in the war against
drug traffickers and fighting with guerrilla and paramilitary
groups financed by drug traffickers.
</P>
<P>
"We hope the U.S. will provide us with technology and we will
bear the possible cost of human casualties. Let us join hand and
go ahead," said Tapias.
</P>
<P>
Tapias, to be accompanied by Defense Minister Luis Fernando
Ramires on his U.S. tour, is scheduled to meet with U.S.
legislators and officials in Washington for talks on more
technical and economic assistance. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
