<DOCNO> XIE19991003.0159 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ecuador's President Visits Evacuees From Volcano Zone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
QUITO, October 2 (Xinhua) -- Ecuadorian President Jamil Mahuad
on Saturday visited the 198 people who were evacuated from their
homes near the active Guagua Pichincha volcano, which is located
12 kilometers west of Quito.
</P>
<P>
The president promised all necessary assistance for the Quito
municipality as well as Tungurahua and Chimborazo provinces that
are threatened by possible eruptions of the volcano.
</P>
<P>
He said that the Quito Metropolitan Municipality had got half
of the 800,000 U.S. dollars budgeted to deal with the emergency,
and pledged the cooperation of the capital citizens with the
people evacuated from the Loa community near the volcano.
</P>
<P>
Quito's residents have been put on "orange alert" since last
Monday after they were given white and yellow alerts against
volcano eruption. The orange alert warning is a level below red,
which would indicate Guagua Pichincha could erupt in hours or days.
A yellow alert means a possible eruption in weeks, months or years.
</P>
<P>
According to the latest official reports, seismic activities of
the volcano diminished Saturday and rocks were observed falling on
the dome, which would indicate an impending eruption.
</P>
<P>
The Pichincha volcano has two main peaks, the active Guagua
Pichincha, and the inactive Rucu Pichincha, which stands as a
natural barrier between the volcano's crater and Quito.
</P>
<P>
Guagua Pichincha's last major eruption was in 1660, when Quito
was covered by 25 centimeters of ash and volcanic fragments in
nine days of eruption. But no one was killed in that eruption.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
