<HEADLINE> Simitis, Lipponen Meet in Athens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, October 2 (Xinhua) -- Greek Prime Minister Costas
Simitis discussed here Saturday with his visiting Finnish
counterpart, Paavo Lipponen, issues concerning the summit of the
European Union (EU) heads of state and governments this months.
</P>
<P>
The summit, which will take place in the Finnish city of
Tampere on October 15 and 16, will mainly tackle asylum and
immigration, the fight against cross-border crime and the forging
of closer ties in the sphere of justice.
</P>
<P>
Both men agreed on the need for the EU to negotiate re-entry
agreements with third countries.
</P>
<P>
Simitis said after the talks that Greece needed tighter control
for the protection of EU external borders and measures against
phenomenon of illegal immigration because Greece was exposed to
the problem of illegal immigration from third poor countries.
</P>
<P>
On his part, Lipponen, who is touring EU capitals in order to
review the topics to be discussed in Tampere with the leaders of
the other 14 member states, said that he hoped the Tampere summit
would adopt decisions leading to greater security and justice in
the EU.
</P>
<P>
Finland is now holding the six-month EU rotating presidency.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
